UIElement.Notes: This is a simple version of the classic Pong video game. The user controls a paddle which they use to bounce a ball toward the computer's paddle. Whichever one gets the ball past the other first wins. Ball angle can be adjusted by moving the paddle as it hits the ball.
Shows a pretty picture of Pong for a few seconds before game starts.
Shows a picture of a happy monkey since the user won.
Sad monkey. User lost.
This is the game state. All game logic occurs here.
computer paddle
user paddle
Returns CompWon if the ball goes past the right side of the screen, UserWon if the ball goes past the left side of the screen, and TimeUp if the time goes past maxPlayTime
Move's the ball by the input offsets.
Input is a paddle object. Returns true if the ball collided with this paddle. False otherwise.
The time that has passed since this game started.
Moves the user paddle according to the vertical component of the position input.
Moves the computer paddle. Takes an input of the frameTime of the last frame so that it can assure that the computer paddle isn't moving faster than its maximum allowed speed.

This is a constant that defines how much of the difference in speed between a paddle and a ball effects the ball. If this value is one, then the ball's vertical velocity will always match that of the paddle that is last colided with.
The time at which the frame before last occured.
The ball's velocity must be stored and cannot be recalculated each frame so that various operations like moving the ball out of an overlap condition with a paddle don't change its overall speed.
The average computers delta y position during the course of a single frame.
The average users delta y position during the course of a single frame. We use this since sometimes the user speed can jump around a lot on a frame by frame basis. This smooths it out.
The maximum speed at which the computer's paddle can move.
